data.content:
**Yes, C# fully supports `stackalloc` with `Span<nint>` and `Span<nuint>`.** It works without requiring `unsafe` context (since C# 7.2+ allows `stackalloc` into a `Span<T>`). Both signed (`nint`) and unsigned (`nuint`) native-sized integers work:

```csharp
Span<nint> span = stackalloc nint[5];
Span<nuint> uspan = stackalloc nuint[3];
```

On this 64-bit system, each element is 8 bytes. On a 32-bit runtime it would be 4 bytes. The only gotcha: `sizeof(nint)` still requires an `unsafe` context — use `nint.Size` instead if you need the element size in safe code.
